							<tr>
								<td bgcolor=midnightblue background="images/bar.jpg" align="middle" height="20"><font color="white"><b>Charter</b></font></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We the members of Circle of the Golden Dragon are dedicated to having fun in Norrath.  We believe that people should not be judged by race, class, or level.  Among the many qualities we prize in our brothers and sisters are Honor, Truth, Loyalty, and Friendship.  Every member of the guild is ready and willing to give his or her life for any other member.  We do not believe in taking advantage of any other member.  We believe that our actions give us our honor. We all try to live up to the high standards of the guild.  Any who requests membership in the guild must first become familiar with its members, hunting with them and dying with them.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td bgcolor=midnightblue background="images/bar.jpg" align="middle" height="20"><font color="white"><b>Policies</b></font></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>1.  New memberships</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The procedure for an interested party to gain membership in the guild is as follows:</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The prospective member will need the recommendation of an existing full member with whom he/she has played with on many occasions and who can vouch for the character of the prospective member.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The sponsoring member will then relay to the prospective member the guild rules and any other guidance the new member may need.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Once this is done, the sponsor must then contact the Recruiting Officer concerning the prospective member.  The Recruiting Officer will then confirm that the sponsor can vouch for this person as well as answer any further questions.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>At this point, if the prospective member and Recruiting Officer mutually agree to continue the application process, any officer may guild invite the new member.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The new member will have a 2-week probationary period during which he/she will have only limited rights.  During this period any officers may remove the new member for any legitimate reason.  The probationary member may not sponsor any new members during this time.  The new member shall be expected attend as many guild events as possible and to support any other guild functions.  This period is to allow the new member as well as the rest of the guild to determine if the new member is a good fit.  If the new member feels that this is not the guild him/her, they may withdraw from the guild with no hard feelings or ill will.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>During this probationary period, the new initiate should not ask for nor expect to receive free equipment from any of the current members nor from the guild Bank account.  This is to ensure that if the new member does not remain in the guild past the probationary period, nobody in the guild feels used.  Of course, anybody is free to DONATE to the new member if they so desire.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>In order for the new recruit to be considered a full member, they *MUST* sign up on the guild website for their member account. They must also sign up to use the guild's forum, where all raids are requested and questions answered. If a new recruit has never signed up for either one of these, they are not considered a full member, nor are they entitled to enlist the guild's assistance for raids until this is done.</td>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The Recruiting Officer shall keep track of the status of the new member's probationary period.  She will then inform the new member as well as the guild when the probationary period expires.  At this point, the new member shall full member status to the Circle of the Golden Dragon website and he/she can add their guilded characters to the Hall of Heroes.  Thenceforth, they shall be considered full members with all the rights of full members.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>

							<tr>
								<td><b>2.  Termination of membership</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The procedure for a full member to leave the Circle of the Golden Dragon requires several things.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>If the user is removing an alternate character from the guild, no notice is required; however it would be good to let an officer know that you are removing your alternate character.  If an officer is not online or available, a 'guild say' comment pertaining to this is all that is required.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>If you are removing your primary character from the guild, we see this as a more serious removal.  Removal of a main character, to place that character into another guild, *REQUIRES* that *ALL* alternate characters are removed as well.  So as not to destroy your chances at returning to Circle of the Golden Dragon again, you need to notify an officer online.  If one was not available online you must post your request to leave in our forum, prior to doing so.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>3.  Guild events:</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>When a planned and posted guild event is to take place, a few things need to be followed.  A guild event is anything--a raid, a camp, or just a gathering--that is posted on the message board or calendar for either the whole guild or eligible levels.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>All guild members that can support the raid or event should attend if possible.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>If a member wishes to invite a guest, it is expected that the member shall make an attempt to check with the rest of the guild to see if any objections exist.  Every attempt should be made to post any proposed invitations on the message board beforehand.  If this can't be done due to time constraints or other reasons, ask in guild chat the other members who are on and are planning to attend the event.  If there are no objections, then the guest may be invited.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>4.  Player conduct</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>A guild member's words and actions reflect directly upon the guild. If one of our members dishonors the guild, the charges are brought before the leading guild council for a vote.  The council, after hearing the particulars of the case, shall decide upon a course of action--up to and including termination of membership.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>5.  Life in the guild</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Certain behaviors are encouraged of the members of the guild. We want to be able to fully trust and believe that ALL of our brothers and sisters will be there to support us when we need it, especially when we are grouped.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Loyalty, honor, courage, sacrifice, friendship, and the list continues are what we desire all members to exhibit at all times.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Some behaviors that will NOT be tolerated (yet are not limited to only these) are:</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Gross disrespect for other guild members and the guild.  Disrespect towards other members includes, but is not limited to, defamation of another member, bidding over another member's bid on an item they have already bid on in an auction, taking advantage of another member in some fashion, and harassing other guild members.  No one is permitted to do any of these in guildsay.  Any problems that you have with a person should be dealth with privately and not open as a public forum for debate.  This will often cause heated debates that will lead to members leaving the guild.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Disrespect for the guild includes, but is not limited to, spreading bad propaganda about the guild, taking actions that would put a bad light upon the guild--i.e. Kill stealing, stealing camps, etc.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>No one is permitted to do any of these in guildsay.  Any problems that you have with a person should be dealth with privately and not in the open as a public forum for debate.  This will often cause heated debates that will lead to members leaving the guild.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The offending member will have their actions brought before the leading guild council general membership who will consider the evidence at hand. The offending member will be given the opportunity to defend him/herself.  The membership will then decide upon a course of action, up to and including dismissal from the guild.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>6.  On equipment:</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>If a member has some spare equipment or time that is needed by another member, it is recommended that they donate the item without asking or demanding recompense; if we all try to do this, none of us will be in need for we all will be watching out for each other.  Also equipment should only be asked for primary characters.  If the donor wishes, of course, they should feel free to donate to secondary characters, etc.  It is also understood that some members are lower in level than others and that some have more money than others, so give what you are able to and when you are higher in abilities you can give back more at that time.  This is not to say that one needs to be a beggar themselves to donate, but we all need to take care of each other and assist when we can.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>7.  On guild groups:</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>A guild group shall be defined as any group consisting solely of members of the guild and invited guests--whether it is merely an impromptu gathering or a planned activity.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Master looting should *ALWAYS* be observed in *ALL* guild groups unless otherwise stated.  This makes the looting fair and also keeps the casters from having to worry about looting when they should be meditating.  If you are not the designated master looter, DO NOT loot.  Any special items will go to the one who needs it and can use it; otherwise a random roll will determine who receives it.  The master looter is responsible to make sure that a split is done before people come and go to ensure that everyone receives a part of the loot for which they fought.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>Also when in a group, you *MUST* listen to the instructions given by the officers and leaders, especially in the middle of a fight.  If there is a disagreement, wait until after the fight to voice them when it is safe again.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>8.  On guild raids:</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>A guild raid is defined as any number of groups consisting solely of members of the guild, allies, and invited guests--whether it is merely an impromptu gathering or a planned activity.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td> Master looting will *ALWAYS* be observed in *ALL* guild  raids. If you are not the designated master looter, DO NOT  loot. Any special items will go to the one who needs it and can use it; otherwise a random roll will determine who receives  it. In regards to the loot that drops during a raid, If the item is a special magic or lore item that someone might want then this item will be rolled on after the raid has  completed. Any 'junk' or 'miscellaneous' items such as Fine Steel weapons and any plat looted during the course of the raid will be sold and added to the guild's RAID  FUND. The raid fund is in place to pay for coffins, peridots, or any items that are expensive and used to recover bodies and/or experience in the case that something goes wrong with the raid and we need to resort to using these items.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>When attending a guild raid, you *ABSOLUTELY MUST* listen to the instructions given by the raid leader.  The group leaders must also try to keep their group members in line with what the raid leader is requesting, especially in the middle of a fight.  If there is a disagreement, wait until after the fight to voice them when it is safe again.  Persons not following orders during the raids may cost the raid party their lives, and those persons will be excluded from further raids for deliberate failure to comply.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>9.  On quests--epic or otherwise</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>In the course of doing quests, if more than one person wishes the guild's assistance to complete them, a list shall be created of the requesting members. The request should appear in our guild's forum and not be requested in guild.&nbsp; We do not normally organize large-scale raids based on who is currently on.&nbsp; Post your request in the forum and an officer will plan  and post the raid for all to see.&nbsp; If the officer is requiring persons to signup in the post, this is to help determine the group layout and whether the raid is possible before assembling and wasting everyone's time waiting around.&nbsp; The order of the requesting list&nbsp;will be appended to and not inserted into.&nbsp; This means that if a level 49 character has been waiting in the list to do a raid for an epic item, a level 56 cannot come along and be inserted above them.&nbsp; The&nbsp;list is added to at the bottom only.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The list will be determined using the following criteria:<BR>First is seniority in the guild.<BR>Next is the level of the character completing the quest with the higher-level character having priority.<BR>Finally a random roll will determine the order among characters of the same level.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>If anyone fails in their quest and loses their quest items, they shall be put at the bottom of the list and will have their chance again only after all the others have been given a chance as well.  This is to ensure that all members will be given a fair chance to obtain the guild's assistance in their many endeavors in a timely manner.</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>10.  On power leveling:</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>The guild DOES NOT exist for the purpose of power leveling people.  This is not to say that we do not do it, but that one should not ASK nor DEMAND it of other members.  It is up to the individual members to OFFER to do it for other members when they have the time.  We particularly DO NOT want to hear as the first few words from any new members to be "Can someone power level me?"</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><b>11.  Guild tags</b></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>&nbsp;</td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td>It is required that all members are not to be anonymous while in the game.  This is for a couple of reasons.  First, this allows other members of the guild to see who is online.  Also, all members should be proud to display their guild tag.  If you wish to hide your stats from others, use the '/roleplay' option so you will still be listed in the online roster.</td>
							</tr>
